SIMPLE: partition
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Partition
<hw>Par*ti"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>partition</ets>, L. <ets>partitio</ets>. See <er>Part</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of parting or dividing;
the state of being parted; separation; division; distribution; <as>as,
the <ex>partition</ex> of a kingdom</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And good from bad find no <qex>partition</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which divides or separates; that by which
different things, or distinct parts of the same thing, are separated;
separating boundary; dividing line or space; specifically, an interior
wall dividing one part or apartment of a house, a compartment of a room,
an inclosure, or the like, from another; <as>as, a brick
<ex>partition</ex>; lath and plaster <ex>partitions</ex>; cubicles with
four-foot high <ex>partitions</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>No sight could pass⟦br⟧
Betwixt the nice <qex>partitions</qex> of the grass.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A part divided off by walls; an apartment; a
compartment.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Lodged in a small
<xex>partition</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law.)</fld> <def>The severance of common or
undivided interests, particularly in real estate. It may be effected by
consent of parties, or by compulsion of law.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A score.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Partition of numbers</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>,
<cd>the resolution of integers into parts subject to given
conditions.</cd> <rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Partition</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Partition
<hw>Par*ti"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Partitioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Partitioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
divide into parts or shares; to divide and distribute; <as>as, to
<ex>partition</ex> an estate among various heirs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To divide into distinct parts by lines, walls, etc.;
<as>as, to <ex>partition</ex> a house</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Uniform without, though severally <qex>partitioned</qex>
within.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>partitioned</ent>⟦br⟧
